commit.message:
Inline wipes in the Options structure.

This does not make much of a difference besides to the size
of the Options structure itself, but it allows copying these
into a per-sheet structure more easily, if needed.

Avoid copying the source image for deskew.

Instead of relying on copying the source image to a new image,
calculate two center areas, and update the formula to expect
them to differ.

This allows skipping one copy per mask, although there is
still a need to copy the result back into the original image.

Move FloatPoint to primitives, calculate center of rectangle.

This is a relatively common operation, it's worth having as a
separate function.

Move the actual image processing for deskew into deskew.c.

Instead of doing the two copies in main(), do them in a
separate function, so that they are kept closer together.

Move logging to the filters.

This improves data locality as the count doesn't need to be returned.

Only save before/after when actually deskewing.

Instead of saving two identical files before and after *detection*
of each mask, save the files before and after the single mask
deskew.
Correct the maximum size of a filename/path.
Move wipes definition inside the Options structure.

Nearly complete the migration of all options to the Options structure.

This still exclude the options that need to be allocated,
but at least it makes it possible to keep the various
options parsing into a single structure from here on.

Hide some of the pre-validation variables away from the processing code.

This moves the temporary variables that are used to store command line
arguments before their validations inside a block that terminates before
processing start.

It ensures that for parameters that need to be calculated or validated,
the processing code only gets access to the latter.

Note that this currently cannot be done for variables that are referenced
as pointers, but that is only the blackfilterExclude array.

When printing parameters, only print the content of the options struct.

This makes sure that particularly for parsed/validated parameters we have gone
through the validation before we provide them to the user as validation.

When applying per-input adjustment, make sure to update them in the parameters.

This wasn't very obvious because all of the temporary variables are still visible
after parameter validations completed.

It also isn't the best design insofar as it allows changes to happen outside
of the validation routines, but it will have to do for now.

Make all parameters structures part of Options.

This changes the various validators for mask/deskew/filters to return a boolean,
and set the various parameters in the Options structure, instead of returning
a new one.

In turn, this makes it easier to split the scope of temporary variables for options
parsing.

Prune some of the unused constants.

These have been mostly reworked into definite structures, though some are still missing.

Rewrite layout parsing as a table lookup.

This also makes the parameter case insensitive.
Avoid a silly substring search where I'm looking for a single character.

Rewrite interpolation parsing as a table lookup.

This matches other options passed in, and makes it case-insensitive.

Rewrite edge parsign and handling.

The new Edge structure has the same size as the previous bitmask, but
simplifies the flow of the code by just accessing forur booleans instead
of using bitwise math.

The parsing is changed and made a lot stricter, allowing only the tokens
themselves instead of a horrible mix of "leftrighttopbottom" which it did
before (despite the man page saying this should be comma-separated.)

On the other hand, the parsing is now case insensitive.

Make directions being a structure of two bools instead of an int of flags.

We only have a handful of these cases, and as it turns out two booleans pack smaller than the `int`.

Simplify wipes parsing and handling by creating a Wipes structure.

Masks should follow soon, this could also allow me to attempt again at making the size dynamic, but for now, ignore it.

Move more of the processed parameters into the Options structure.

Eventually, the option parsing should only leave a read-only Options structure, that the processing
can then take as input and read from, without ever having to change the values.

Remove parseInts/parseFloats parsers in favour of explicit validating parsers.

Not all of the options are particularly regular, so we still have a cop-out to parse symmetric ints and floats.

On the other hand, this allows passing more explicitly typed objects to the parameter validators, which is good.

Declare calculated parameters together with definition.

Instead of using old-C style by keeping all of the variables declared at the top of main(), move the declaration together with the calculation, enforcing the non initialized variables can't even be referenced.

Rework physical dimensions parsing.

This is a significant change in the parsing of physical dimension and (paper) sizes compared to previously.

PPI (formerly referred to as DPI) calculation is applied only after all options have been parsed, which means it is no longer possible to mix parameters with different PPI interpretation.

This would allow using dimension parsing more widely as it is now much more reliable, if not very optimised.

Internal calculation has moved to integer mils (1/1000th of an inch) rather than floating inches, which caused some of the golden files to ever so slightly increase in size (1px on the vertical.)

As mils is now used internally, accept mils as a valid unit (together with mm, cm, and in.)

And instead of only accepting a3/4/5 and letter/legal, include the whole A0~A10 series, but keep the more common formats higher in the table.

tests: print the generated command line.

This just makes it easier to copy-paste from logs to the
terminal to run this in gdb.

Move math_util.h to lib/

There is nothing in this file that is particularly
about image processing, and it is useful to have
it available to other parts of the code
very explicitly.

Replace size usage with RectangleSize variables.

This includes a new coerce_size, as in
many cases we replace -1 with an external
size definition.

Make parseSize return a RectangleSize.

This also required creating a parseDelta, and making some
of the parameters explicit sizes or deltas.

Make it easier to build a sub-tree of meson environments.

This will come useful for cross-compilation as well as for benchmarks.

Make set_pixel a void return.

Instead of actually counting how many pixels were turned, just
return an approximation in the grayfilter like in everything else.

This allows dropping further counters and the boolean return.
